I"!<p><a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">Dynamical systems</a>, both <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/continuous-state-dynamical-systems-share-a-common-structure">continuous-state</a> and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/finite-state-dynamical-systems-are-diverse">finite-state</a> ones, exhibit <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/memory-is-perception-of-structural-artifacts">memory</a>. This is due to the fact that the current location in <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">state space</a> is <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/momentum-in-optimization-is-trend-observation-in-retrospective-futurism">influenced by all previous locations</a>. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/recurrent-networks-approximate-dynamical-systems">Recurrent neural networks</a> use this memory in resolving <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/short-long-term-is-a-spectrum-for-memory">short-term dependencies</a>.</p>
